com.samsung.android.service.health.tracking

Class HealthTracker

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.samsung.android.service.health.tracking.HealthTracker

  • public class HealthTracker
extends Object
    HealthTracker enables an application to set an event listener and receive the Galaxy Watch's sensor data for a specific HealthTrackerType.

    Before getting a HealthTracker instance, check the Galaxy Watch's capabilities using:

    • HealthTrackerCapability.getSupportHealthTrackerTypes()

           // Connection with Health Platform succeeded. Check capability.
     List<HealthTrackerType> availableTrackers = healthTrackingService.getTrackingCapability().getSupportHealthTrackerTypes();
     if (!availableTrackers.contains(HealthTrackerType.ECG_ON_DEMAND)) {
         // Tracking Electrocardiogram (ECG) On-Demand is not available.
         // Display a proper message to the user. 
     } else {
         ecgTracker = healthTrackingService.getHealthTracker(HealthTrackerType.ECG_ON_DEMAND);
     }

    Since:
    1.0.0
    See Also:
    HealthTracker.TrackerEventListener
    HealthTrackerType

    • Method Detail

      • setEventListener

        public void setEventListener(HealthTracker.TrackerEventListener listener)
        Set an event listener for this HealthTracker instance. If it succeeds, the event listener exists and retrieves sensor data until the unsetEventListener() call.

        Only 1 HealthTrackerType's event listener can be set in 1 application.
        Adding multiple event listeners for the same HealthTrackerType in 1 application is unavailable.

        Parameters:
        listener - an implemented TrackerEventListener.
        Since:
        1.0.0

      • setExerciseData

        public void setExerciseData(DataType type,
                            float[] data,
                            long[] timestamp)
        Set exercise data along with timestamp, to get sweat loss data.
        Parameters:
        type - a data type to set exercise data like DataType.STEP_PER_MINUTE.
        data - an array of exercise data corresponding to DataType.STEPS_PER_MINUTE in ExerciseUpdateListener.onExerciseUpdate().
        timestamp - an array of timestamp for each exercise data point.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the data array size is more than 200 or the data value is negative.
        IllegalArgumentException - if the timestamp array is not sorted or values are not in Epoch.
        IllegalArgumentException - if the timestamp values are earlier than starting the exercise.
        IllegalStateException - if this method is called before setExerciseState( ExerciseState.START) is called.
        Since:
        1.0.0

      • setExerciseState

        public void setExerciseState(ExerciseState state)
        Set an exercise state.

        Setting ExerciseState.START again in the same application is ignored if the exercise was started already.
        If another application calls setExerciseState( ExerciseState.START), the first application's exercise is automatically terminated and sweat loss data for it is returned. The other application then works normally.

        Parameters:
        state - An exercise state with ExerciseState.START or ExerciseState.STOP.
        Throws:
        IllegalStateException - if it is called before setEventListener(HealthTracker.TrackerEventListener).
        IllegalStateException - if setExerciseState( ExerciseState.STOP) is called before setExerciseState( ExerciseState.START).
        Since:
        1.0.0

      • unsetEventListener

        public void unsetEventListener()
        Stop the registered event listener for this HealthTracker instance.
        Since:
        1.0.0

      • flush

        public boolean flush()
        Flush gathered health data. This method provides collected data instantly.
        After flushing data, the registered event listener will work continuously.

        For example, if an event listener for HealthTrackerType.HEART_RATE_CONTINUOUS has been registered, the Health Platform gathers heart rate data until the batch data is retrieved periodically. If 120 heart rate data were gathered and flush() is called, the Health Platform sends an event to the TrackerEventListener.onFlushCompleted and the gathered 120 data is retrieved in TrackerEventListener.onDataReceived.
        Afterwards, the Health Platform gathers heart rate data again and sends the gathered data with a batch process.

        Only the following tracker types support the flush() API. Otherwise, it returns false.

        • HealthTrackerType.PPG_CONTINUOUS
        • HealthTrackerType.HEART_RATE_CONTINUOUS
        • HealthTrackerType.ACCELEROMETER_CONTINUOUS
        • HealthTrackerType.SKIN_TEMPERATURE_CONTINUOUS

        Returns:
        true if the flush was successful.
        false if the flush failed or no event listener was registered.
        Since:
        1.0.0
        See Also:
        setEventListener(HealthTracker.TrackerEventListener)
        HealthTracker.TrackerEventListener.onFlushCompleted
        Remark:
        This API is not intended for periodic or frequent calls.
